<Author>jeanninelehman
<Content>Charm, location, and a warm staff. After reading several magazines and newspaper articles on small boutique hotels in Paris, I picked this hotel for our last two nights. We needed two beds, and was told they would accommmodate us, albeit we must change rooms.Juliette was wonderful upon our check-in - very helpful and friendly and she speaks great English! She was truly helpful to us! She even gave us specific instructions on how to get to a great restaurant in the 7th using the metro. Salome was wonderful too.The rooms have typical French Provincial wallpaper. The first room at $138 E. was spacious and had a comfortable bed. We had to make up the second bed sitting outside our door, though. The second room, at $118 E was much smaller and the bed was not as comfortable. Both were facing the courtyard and were fairly quiet except for the sound of suitcases rolling down the cobblestones. Bathrooms are newly renovated and nice, but with very narrow and short bathtubs. The room in the main building was served by an elevator, but pulling a suitcase up 33 stairs in the front building was not fun!We did not take their breakfast (8 E.) as there were several nice bakeries nearby. Also nearby were two metro stops, so you can get anyplace easily!The reservation process was easy and I heard back from them via the internet right away.Note that if you want coffee in the morning, it is $3 E. A lady from New Zealand had her own coffee and they provided hot water for her to make her own.All in all, it was a pleasant stay and a reasonable price. If you go and it is a weekend,I hope Juliette is there. Be sure to say hello.Enjoy! 
