<Author>fromTorontoTravel
<Content>What a Paris Hotel should be! My sister-in-law and I stayed at this hotel last year - we left our husbands and kids at home and decided to see Paris from a ladies' point-of view. We originally planned a stay of 12 nights but decided to shorten our Paris adventure and head to the Provence area for a few days. I gave the hotel two-week notice of our change of plans and received an immediate confirmation and OK from the front desk. We took a shuttle from the airport which was a great move - great value plus we had the benefit of the friendly, experienced driver acting as a tour-guide, pointing out all the great spots of interest around Paris. The Hotel courtyard that greeted us was spectacular! Check out all the posted pictures - the courtyard is private, beautifully landscaped and oh, so French. The check-in was smooth, we had a comfortable, nicely decorated room on the second floor with a great view of the courtyard. Now, we did not go to Paris to watch TV or hang out in our room so we immediately set out to scope out the neighbourhood. To our great surprise, we discovered Rue Moufftard and it's market and shops with Cafe Marc serving one of the best and least expensive coffies in Paris. We found a seat every time we visited (there is no take-out coffee here - sit and enjoy). While strolling, we ate a croissant or a goodie from one of the numerous neighbourhood bakeries so breakfast was always exciting and new. I thought the breakfast at the hotel was pricey so we just found other alterernatives. For lunch, we again picked up something from the market and ate back at the hotel in the lovely courtyard, surrounded by the lovely scents, bird songs as well the the sound of the childrens' choir coming from the nearby school. It was fabulous! The location of this hotel is ideal - we walked everywhere (resulting in a 10lbs loss in weight for each of us during our 2 week stay in France): The church of Notre Dame, the Pantheon, Luxenburg gardens, thousands of shops and restaurants of the Latin quater...Upon returning to Paris after our trip south, we had to stay in another nearby hotel - it was more expensive but what a dump by comparison! Please don't complain about room sizes or hospitality in Hotel des Grandes Ecoles until you've seen other Parisian options, and we did see at least a dozen - yuck! We so wished that our Gem of a hotel was again available but they do book up early. After all, it keeps appearing as one of the best values in Paris in many of the Travel books. We both agreed! I can't wait to go back. 
