<Content>Beautiful bargain, but beware of bedbugs We stayed for a week in a room on the top floor in June '03, so perhaps (hopefully) the problem has long been fixed. The hotel is a delightful and serene well-priced haven, as others have noted. But in the middle of the night near the end of our stay, I was up and noticed a lot of small dots moving in the bathroom. Lights on!! Ditto for the bed. Black spots on the sheets, too. The next morning itchy bumps were rising on my arms and hands. Apparently, it's typical for it to take a number of days of bites for the body to develop an allergic reaction. We told the staff, who did not seem surprised about the bugs, and they sprayed the room. Unfortunately, this had no effect and the previous night's adventure was repeated. We checked out, with our lower arms covered in bites. The hotel's owners were not very interested in the problem, and offered no compensation. When we returned home, it ook over a week for the itching and bumps to subside. Needless to say, we left all our luggage outside and fumigated it before bringing it into the house. Another problem with our top-floor room was the heat. There was no AC, and in the first week of June 03, this already made it quite difficult to sleep, and impossible to cool off when returning to the room at the end of the day to get ready for dinner. (later that summer, there were a record number of deaths from a heat wave in Europe) Today's article in the NY Times travel section says that AC is only needed about 4 weeks in the summer in Paris - I think it's more like 4 months. We were in Paris in late June 05 with no AC, and were sweltering. Also, in late July in the Swiss mountains last year, it was over 90F for several days. I think foregoing AC in the summer in Europe will no longer do, with hotter summers becoming pretty typical there. 
