<Content>Wonderful Hotel des Grandes Ecoles experience We have just returned from 7 nights at the Hotel de Grandes Ecoles and have fallen in love with both the hotel and with Paris. Our room on the third floor overlooked the courtyard, with wide windows that opened out letting in birdsong, the sound of nearby church bells, and a wonderful, elusive fragrance that we couldn't identify. We could only bring ourselves to close the windows when the wind drove the rain into our room, which was very comfortable and charmingly decorated. The bathroom was attractive as well, with a fine in-tub shower, scented soaps and shampoos, a hair dryer and plenty of towels. True there is no television, radio, or mini-bar; but those are items we do our best to avoid on vacations, so that absence goes in the plus column for us. The breakfast is essentially what we would term a continental one and not worth the 8euro each; although, again, it is charmingly presented. We preferred to buy delicious pain au chocolat from a marvelous little boulangerie in Place Contrascarpe, a two minute walk away, and bring them back to a table in the lovely courtyard. It was a challenge that we could not meet to locate any place that could provide take away tea, but we discovered that we could purchase it from the hotel for 3euro. worth it for a habitual tea drinker! The staff were pleasant and helpful, the price a reasonable 115 euro for two. This hotel will definitely be our Paris location on future visits. 
