<Author>Princeton_Man
<Content>Great hotel, great location I find it hard to believe the last reviewer and I stayed at the same hotel. My wife and I just returned from four days and I have to say it was as terrific as so many dozens of American travellers and travel writers have said. Yes, the rooms are smaller and the walls are not sound-proof. That's true of all older hotels in France. And in this hotel, there are big differences room-to-room. We were first offered a room on the ground floor, but it had only a double bed - too small for us. When I asked for a different room with a bigger bed we were offered something on the second floor that was bigger, had a queen size bed and a full size tub/shower in the bathroom. Big difference -- same price. We stayed in room 134. It was at the end of the upstairs hallway and had a big window that opened over the beautiful central courtyard. When you reserve, ask for an upstairs room.The breakfast was surperb. We didn't take it the first day because the area is loaded with fabulous bakeries. So on the first morning I ventured out in search of rolls, fruit and coffee to bring back to the room. Alas, it is very easy to buy any kind of warm fresh baked good you can imagine in this neighborhood. But they don't sell coffee at the bakeries. One needs to go to a cafe -- take out coffee in paper cups is unheard of in Paris. So the next two mornings we took the petit dejuner at the hotel. The coffee is about the best I've ever tasted --rich and dark --and the croissants were freshly baked.The location is an oasis in a very lively neighborhood at the Rue Mouffetard, packed with cafes, bars, stores and hundreds of pedestrians -- mostly a student crowd. There is a jazz bar around the corner that made noise until about 2 AM on Friday night but was quiet on Saturday night.A few other tips - The Rue Cardinal Metro station is closed for at least the next few months for repairs, which meant we had to use the Jussieu stop and go up the hill on Rue des Boulangers.Taxis - Unlike NYC and other big cities, one cannot flag down a cab on the street in Paris. You need to have the hotel call for a cab or go to a taxi stand. The nearest one to the hotel is at the junction of Blvd St Germain and Rue Monge - a decent walk. We also got to and from the CDG airport on the RER line B using the Luxembourg station on Blvd St-Michel. You get a great view of the Pantheon on this walk and the neighborhood seems very safe. This was a big savings over a $60 cab ride. 
