<Content>Loved Hotel des Grandes Ecole Have just returned from Paris France on Friday 04/02/05. Spent 4 nights at Hotel Des Grandes Ecoles in the Latin Quarter. This hotel is in an excellent location for all your sightseeing. The rooms are small and very parisien, they are cleaned every day and breakfast is at a supplement if you so wish. We had a lovely time staying here, there is a lovely courtyard to the front and it is very safe and quiet.   From our hotel we were only 5 mins walk away from the Pantheon and only 10-15 mins walk from Notre Dame Cathedral. We walked everywhere in paris including the Sacre Coeur, never had to use the metro underground. Our hotel was within walking distance for bars, restaurants etc, highly recommend La Vulcan, food was superb along with the price 鈧?4 euros for two people for 3 course meal, drinks not included but they don't start serving until after 7.00pm.  If you are staying in the Latin Quarter and are looking for a pub at night and your french is not the best then go for a quiet drink to The Fifth Avenue Pub on Rue Mouffetard. The barman Roddy is from Glasgow and is a real gentleman, we had the best of craic with him and the other barperson Annmarie from Dublin was lovely. They have satellite tv and show all the big sport events.  Its best to shop around for snacks during the day. For breakfast outside of the hotel find yourself a columbas cafe, two teas and croissants were only 鈧? euros for two, we paid double that elsewhere. We also used the Le Marche FranPrix supermarkets they were very reasonable for sandwiches drinks etc and then eat them as you walk along or there are plenty of nice places to sit and watch the world go by.  If you are going to the Sacre Coeur walk through the Opera District and up through Montmarte it's absolutely beautiful don't take Boulevard Sebastopol, not nice at all. Beware of the guys at the bottom of the Sacre Coeur who will try to stop you and sell you bracelets made from wool strings for 鈧? euros a piece, its a rip off but they do it with such charm, that you aren't aware until its too late.  Do try to speak the language whilst you are there, in our experience the french really appreciate it if you at least try, even if its incorrect. They will speak back to you in English if you get into difficulty. We only had basic school french but it got us by  PS Recommend the Paris Shuttle from Charles De Gaulle airport to the door of your hotel, service was excellent well worth the extra few euros.  Traffic in Paris is an experience all of its own, an absolute nightmare especially around the Arc De Triomphe.  Paris was everything I thought it would be and more, a truly romantic city and the architecture was superb, we had a great few days there.  
